The '''Video DAC''' is a chip on the N64 motherboard that converts the 7-bit-wide synchronous [[Video Interface]] output to analog video.

Early revisions pair a discrete Video DAC (VDC-NUS or VDC-NUS A) with an external encoder (ENC-NUS or S-RGB A) to generate video output.<ref>S-RGB A appears exclusively on NUS-001(FRA) models. While this encoder is RGB-capable, the necessary amplification components are unpopulated on the motherboard, leaving the signal disconnected from the Multi-AV out port in retail units. S-RGB A lacks S-Video encoding entirely, limiting unmodified NUS-CPU(R)-01 boards to composite output.</ref> Other revisions consolidate these functions into a single integrated chip (DENC-NUS, AVDC-NUS, MAV-NUS).<ref>Later PAL revisions NUS-CPU(P)-03 and -03-1 lack S-Video output due to board-level omissions; the Luma (Y) and Chroma (C) traces from the MAV-NUS encoder are physically severed and the supporting surface-mount components are unpopulated.</ref>

== Bus Operation ==

The Video DAC operates at four times the pixel clock frequency. Four consecutive VI clock cycles are multiplexed over the VI bus to form one 21-bit color value per emitted pixel.

* 1 pixel = 4 VI clocks
* 7 bits × 3 channels = 21-bit RGB

[[File:N64videosys.png|thumb|Video DAC bus and waveform diagram. Image from: [https://web.archive.org/web/20090103080549/http://members.optusnet.com.au/eviltim/n64rgb/n64rgb.html Tim Worthington - RGB Video DAC for Nintendo 64]]]

The 4-cycle sequence carries both pixel data and control signals and restarts whenever !DSYNC is low.

The Video Interface transmits control signals every clock during blanking by holding !DSYNC low across multiple VI clock cycles.

